## What Black Box is

Black Box is a local flight recorder for AI coding agents. It is not an agent and
does not control or sandbox one. It records observable evidence so a developer can
investigate what an agent saw, returned, ran, printed, and changed.

High-level flow:

    agent/client
      -> byte-faithful local proxy
      -> configured OpenAI-compatible provider
      -> crash-safe SQLite journal and content-addressed blobs
      -> protocol normalization
      -> client-visible context reconstruction
      -> process and workspace evidence
      -> deterministic blame/anomaly analysis
      -> incident report, local cockpit, or portable .bbx archive

Important product principles:

- Evidence stays local by default.
- Raw observed evidence, deterministic derived evidence, inference, and
  unknown/missing evidence remain distinct.
- Authorization and cookie values may be forwarded but are not persisted.
- Normal analysis and reporting are local. Optional AI-written report enrichment
  requires explicit consent.
- Black Box does not expose chain-of-thought or provider-hidden instructions.
- It does not claim to prove private model causation.
- Blame output is an evidence-backed hypothesis with provenance, counterevidence,
  alternatives, confidence limits, and missing-evidence warnings.

Recommended installed use:

    blackbox run -- <agent-command> [arguments...]

From source:

    npm run blackbox -- run -- <agent-command> [arguments...]

The child must honor the injected OpenAI-compatible base URL for provider-traffic
capture. Wrapped-process and workspace evidence still work around the child process.

## Completed product scope

The planned M0 through M9 source-candidate path is implemented:

- Typed canonical evidence contracts and versioned schemas.
- Crash-safe SQLite storage and content-addressed payload blobs.
- Byte-faithful OpenAI-compatible recording proxy.
- Chat Completions and Responses JSON/SSE normalization.
- Wrapped-process lifecycle, bounded output, signal forwarding, and exit
  preservation.
- Git-aware and plain-directory baselines and authoritative final diffs.
- Approximate live observations kept distinct from final evidence.
- Local authenticated React cockpit with timeline, context, diff, blame, report,
  and raw-evidence views.
- Client-visible context reconstruction, including Responses ancestry.
- Deterministic blame ranking, anomaly detection, counterevidence, and limitations.
- Deterministic Markdown/JSON reports and optional consent-gated AI prose.
- Tamper-evident .bbx export/import, retention, quota, deletion, and garbage
  collection.
- Adapter integration contract. No completed agent-specific adapter is bundled in
  0.1.0.
- Deterministic offline demo and seeded rogue-agent incident.
- Cross-platform CI and packed-artifact installation tests on Linux, macOS, and
  Windows.
- Apache-2.0 licensing, third-party notices, security verification, and a complete
  newcomer guide.

Read these instead of reconstructing implementation details from memory:

- docs/complete-project-guide.md: complete newcomer-oriented project guide.
- README.md: product overview, quickstart, CLI, and feature summary.
- plan.md: milestone and implementation history.
- design.md: product and design reasoning.
- docs/release-checklist.md: release boundaries and gates.
- docs/security-verification.md: security controls and regression coverage.
- docs/privacy.md: evidence and privacy boundaries.
- docs/protocol-support.md: supported and unsupported protocols.
- docs/archive-format.md: portable .bbx behavior.
- docs/adapter-authoring.md: adapter integration contract.
- docs/decisions/: architecture decisions 0001 through 0010.

