## Recommended first release

The shipping plan already explained to the user is:

1. Confirm npm scope ownership and enable npm 2FA.
2. Keep the GitHub repository public for provenance.
3. Prepare seven runtime packages, documentation, and READMEs.
4. Run all local gates and commit a clean candidate.
5. Push the exact SHA only with user authorization.
6. Wait for all GitHub CI jobs on that SHA.
7. Bootstrap the first packages from a protected GitHub Actions environment with a
   short-expiry granular npm token.
8. Publish all seven as public packages under the next dist-tag with provenance,
   dependencies first and CLI last.
9. Install and verify the real registry artifacts.
10. Sign and push v0.1.0 at the tested SHA.
11. Promote support packages and then CLI from next to latest.
12. Publish the GitHub release.
13. Revoke the bootstrap token and configure npm trusted publishing for all seven.

Why next first: ordinary installs follow latest. Publishing under next allows the
real registry artifacts to be tested before normal users receive them.

Why a bootstrap workflow: GitHub Actions can generate provenance for the public
repository and exact commit. Trusted publishing cannot be configured until each
package exists, so first creation needs a one-time credential or interactive local
publish. The one-time protected workflow is recommended.

